text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%0a!Inversion in Embedded Questions%0a%0a:Author: rachelc%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aSubject-auxiliary inversion in embedded questions of some varieties of English%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThis morphosyntactic alteration is called inversion in embedded questions and it can be found in Hiberno and Belfast English as well as in several North American varieties of English, including African American, Appalachian, Chicano, Northest US, and Newfoundland English.%0a%0aAn embedded question is a question which occurs as a subordinate clause rather than as a main clause in a sentence. For example, consider the question “What time is it?” Here, this question is the main clause of the sentence, but an example of this question as an embedded question would be “He doesn’t know what time it is”. %0a%0aIn Standard American English, questions exhibit flipping of the subject and auxiliary verb: “it is 4pm” becomes “what time is it” to form a question. However, this flipping does not occur when forming embedded questions. In the example above, the subject-auxiliary word order in the question is “is it” but in the embedded question is “it is”.%0a%0aHowever, in dialects of English which have inversion in embedded questions, this word order is the same between questions and embedded questions, specifically that it follows the word order of the question. Taking the previous example, some dialects of English would say “He doesn’t know what time is it”. %0a%0aOne thing to note about embedded question inversion is that a complementizer, such as if or whether, is not allowed when a question exhibits inversion. For example, consider the Standard American sentence “He’s wondering whether the test is today.” The inverted sentence “He’s wondering is the test today” is acceptable, but the sentence “He’s wondering whether is the test today” is not because a complementizer and inversion cannot occur in the same sentence. %0a%0aSource: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/inversion-embedded-questions %0a %0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)
